    <h2>Survey Overview and Methodology</h2>
    <p>Understanding how chemical manufacturers approach asset integrity management is essential for benchmarking performance and identifying improvement opportunities. This survey captured responses from over 150 integrity professionals across specialty chemical, commodity chemical, and agrochemical operations, representing facilities of all sizes from single-unit plants to multi-site enterprises.</p>
    <p>Respondents included integrity managers, corrosion engineers, inspection supervisors, and plant managers, providing a broad perspective on AIM practices, challenges, and priorities across the chemical manufacturing sector.</p>

    <h2>Current State of AIM in Chemical Manufacturing</h2>
    <p>The survey revealed significant variation in AIM maturity across the chemical sector. While large, publicly traded chemical companies generally have well-established programs, mid-sized and specialty chemical operations often lag behind. Key findings include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>62% of respondents</strong> still rely on spreadsheets or paper-based systems as their primary tool for managing inspection data.</li>
      <li><strong>Only 38%</strong> have implemented risk-based inspection programs, compared to over 60% in the petroleum refining sector.</li>
      <li><strong>71%</strong> identified data management as their single greatest integrity challenge, followed by staffing (54%) and regulatory compliance (48%).</li>
      <li><strong>45%</strong> reported experiencing at least one unplanned shutdown related to equipment integrity in the past three years.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Technology Adoption Trends</h2>
    <p>Despite the current reliance on manual tools, the survey showed strong intent to invest in AIM technology. Over 55% of respondents indicated plans to evaluate or implement dedicated AIM software within the next two years. The primary drivers cited were regulatory compliance requirements, the need for better risk visibility, and the desire to reduce manual data management effort.</p>
    <p>When evaluating solutions, chemical manufacturers prioritize ease of use, corrosion management capabilities, and integration with existing CMMS platforms. Mobile data collection was identified as a high-priority capability by 67% of respondents, reflecting the need to improve field data quality and timeliness.</p>
    <p>Platforms like <strong>Visions Enterprise</strong> that address the full spectrum of chemical manufacturing integrity needs, including specialized damage mechanism libraries for chemical service, configurable inspection workflows, and proven CMMS integrations, are well positioned to serve this growing market.</p>

    <h2>Implications and Recommendations</h2>
    <p>The survey results point to a sector at an inflection point. Regulatory pressure, aging infrastructure, and workforce turnover are converging to make the status quo unsustainable for many chemical manufacturers. Organizations that act now to implement comprehensive AIM programs will gain competitive advantages in safety performance, operational reliability, and regulatory compliance.</p>
    <p>For chemical manufacturers beginning their AIM journey, the survey data suggests starting with data centralization and corrosion management as the foundational capabilities, then layering on RBI and advanced analytics as organizational maturity develops. This phased approach aligns with both budget realities and the need to build internal capability progressively.</p>
